d as part of that in always interested in understanding the views of all interested parties.</p><p> </p><p>Treasury Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery. Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel" target="_blank">http://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel</a></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","37117 ; 37283 ; 37284","2016-05-23T15:55:03.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518943/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518943/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518943/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-18","Employee Ownership: Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what (a) meetings he has had with external organisations and (b) steps he has taken to encourage the take up of employee share ownership schemes in small and medium-sized businesses in the last 12 months; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","37285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518944","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-23","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) does not routinely record the information requested, but has published estimates on an ad hoc basis since 2008.</p><p> </p><p>In 2008 HMRC published figures for the number of umbrella workers in a consultation document “Tax Relief for travel expenses: temporary workers and overarching employment contracts.” HMRC estimated that around 120 umbrella companies operating in the UK were using overarching contracts and employed around 100,000 temporary workers at any one time.</p><p> </p><p>Evidence suggests that for 2013-14 the 50 largest umbrella companies alone employed 150,000 individuals over the course of a year. In 2015 an estimated 430,000 individuals were employed by umbrella companies and employment agencies on overarching contracts over the course of a year. The number at any one time will be less than this.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-05-23T15:55:06.17Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518944/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518944/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518944/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-18","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what information HM Revenue and Customs holds on the number of people engaged in employment through an umbrella company in each year since 2008.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","37220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518945","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Government will publicise the scheme in good time ahead of its introduction through a range of digital and non-digital channels.</p><p> </p><p>HM Revenue and Customs will also work with the childcare industry and representative groups who interact regularly with parents to raise awareness of the scheme.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-05-26T15:45:50.79Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518945/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518945/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518945/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-18","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 6.9 of the Childcare and early years survey of parents 2014-15, what progress HM Revenue and Customs is making in raising awareness of the tax-free childcare scheme.","false","Biography information for Craig Williams","Cardiff North","Craig Williams","37261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518946","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-26","<p>We do not anticipate that the review of Atos contracts will affect the preparations for the launch of Tax-Free Childcare. The Cabinet Office will write to the PAC summarising the findings of the review and it will be completed in summer 2016.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-05-26T15:42:59.78Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518946/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518946/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518946/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-18","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Government's review of Atos contracts will affect the preparations for the launch of tax-free childcare.","false","Biography information for Craig Williams","Cardiff North","Craig Williams","37264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518947","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-26","<p>Tax-Free Childcare will be launched from early 2017. To roll out the scheme in a safe and managed way, we will be gradually opening up the scheme to all eligible parents within 12 months.</p><p> </p><p>We will provide further details of the exact plans for this rollout in due course and in good time for parents and childcare providers to prepare for the introduction of Tax-Free Childcare.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-05-26T15:41:26.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518947/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518947/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518947/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-18","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, on what dates in 2017 tax-free childcare is planned to be made available to children aged (a) 0-2, (b) 3-4, (c) 5-6, (d) 7-8, (e) 9-10 and (f) 11-12 years.","false","Biography information for Craig Williams","Cardiff North","Craig Williams","37265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518948","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-23","<p>This is an operational matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), who are operationally independent from Government.</p><p> </p><p>The question has been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the honourable member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-05-23T13:55:00.653Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518948/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518948/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518948/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-18","Financial Institutions: Conduct","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Answer of 11 March 2016 to Question 30254, what penalty and enforcement options are currently available to the Financial Conduct Authority if financial institutions fail to meet their obligations in relation to Politically Exposed Persons.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","37102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518949","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-24","<p>Autumn Statement 2015 referenced £800 million allocated to HM Revenue and Customs at Summer Budget 2015 to tackle evasion and non-compliance.</p><p> </p><p>The £800 million will fund the following projects:</p><ul><li><p>Tax Credit Debt Recovery</p></li><li><p>Criminal Investigations</p></li><li><p>Wealthy: enhanced compliance</p></li><li><p>Tackling the hidden economy</p></li><li><p>Additional Compliance Resource: local compliance</p></li><li><p>Tackling illicit tobacco and alcohol</p></li><li><p>Large Business: enhanced compliance</p></li><li><p>Specialist Personal Tax: enhanced compliance</p><p> </p></li></ul>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-05-24T13:54:49.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518949/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518949/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518949/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-18","Revenue and Customs: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Autumn Statement of 25 November 2015, Official Report, column 1361, if he will place in the Library an itemised breakdown of to which HM Revenue and Customs' projects and programmes he has allocated the additional £800 million announced in that statement.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","37103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518950","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-26","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) undertakes a broad range of civil compliance activity to tackle offshore tax evasion. No definitive year by year assessment of the total number of HMRC investigations applying civil sanctions is recorded. Over 1,100 cases of offshore evasion are currently under investigation, with more than 90 individuals currently being investigated for offshore offences.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-05-26T10:54:48.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518950/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518950/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518950/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-18","Tax Evasion","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the contribution of the Financial Secretary to the Treasury on 13 April 2016, Official Report, column 374, how many (a) cases of offshore tax evasion were investigated by HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) and (b) individuals were subject to criminal investigation for offshore tax evasion by HMRC in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","37101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518951","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-23","<p>The issues raised are a matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) who are operationally independent from Government.</p><p> </p><p>These questions have been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the honourable member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","37518","2016-05-23T13:53:27.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518951/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518951/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518951/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-18","Financial Services: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, on how many occasions the Financial Conduct Authority has reported fraudulent activity in the financial services sector to the police or prosecuting authorities in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","37276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518952","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-23","<p>The tax rates for the Soft Drinks Industry Levy have not yet been set. The levy will not capture drinks with an alcoholic content above 0.5% ABV, which cannot be purchased by children.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-05-23T13:49:25.73Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518952/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518952/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518952/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-18","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Government's policy on the soft drinks levy will lead to a higher rate of tax per volume of product levied on some soft drinks than on some non-spirit alcoholic beverages.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","37316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518953","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-23","<p>The aim of the soft drinks industry levy is to help tackle obesity by encouraging producers to reformulate their overall product mixes by reducing added sugar content, helping their customers to choose low-sugar and sugar-free brands, and by reducing the portion sizes for high sugar drinks.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-05-23T13:58:48.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518953/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518953/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518953/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-18","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the aim of the Government's policy on the new soft drinks levy is to persuade manufacturers to stop selling the regular full sugar versions of their drinks products.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","37318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518954","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-23","<p>The tax rates for the Soft Drinks Industry Levy have not yet been set. The levy has been designed to encourage producers to reformulate their overall product mixes, and it is up to the industry how they respond to it. For example, if producers reformulate, they will pay less.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-05-23T13:59:35.81Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518954/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518954/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518954/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-18","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will estimate the potential effect of the introduction of the soft drinks industry levy on the cost of the average weekly shop in real terms in each year to 2018-19.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","37319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518955","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-23","<p>As the Chancellor announced at Budget, the levy will not be charged to the smallest operators. We will consult on the most appropriate mechanism for achieving this.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-05-23T14:05:41.337Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518955/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518955/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518955/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-18","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, at what threshold importers of soft drinks from outside the UK would be liable for the soft drinks industry levy.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","37320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518956","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-23","<p>In 2015 we ran a competitive bidding round that provided an opportunity for Local Enterprise Partnerships to submit bids for a new round of Enterprise Zones.</p><p>All Local Enterprise Partnerships within Yorkshire successfully submitted bids for new Zones or extensions to existing ones. We announced two new Enterprise Zones in November, in Leeds and York, and at Budget we announced an extension to the existing Sheffield Enterprise Zone that is subject to local approval.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-05-23T14:34:41.6Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518956/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518956/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518956/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-18","Enterprise Zones: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with local enterprise partnerships in Yorkshire about the creation of new enterprise zones.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","37385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518957","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-23","<p>We will launch a formal consultation covering various aspects of the proposed levy this summer and we are developing the consultation questions now. The consultation will be open to anyone to respond.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-05-23T13:51:09.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518957/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518957/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518957/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-18","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, who he plans to consult about the soft drinks industry levy; and when that consultation will be launched.","false","Biography information for Caroline Ansell","Eastbourne","Caroline Ansell","37453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518958","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-24","<p>Information on the cost of pensions tax relief is published in HM Revenue and Customs’ National Statistics table PEN6, available on GOV.UK: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/registered-pension-schemes-cost-of-tax-relief" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/registered-pension-schemes-cost-of-tax-relief</a></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-05-24T14:03:07.16Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518958/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518958/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518958/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-18","Tax Allowances: Personal Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the (a) average amount in tax relief paid per higher rate tax relief payer and (b) total amount of tax relief for personal pension payments was in (i)  2013-14 and (ii) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","37403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518959","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-23","<p>The Office for National Statistics have not yet published an estimate of how the Yorkshire economy has grown following the announcement of the Long Term Economic Plan for Yorkshire and Northern Lincolnshire in February 2015.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-05-23T16:13:31.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518959/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518959/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518959/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-18","Economic Growth: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress he has made in increasing the long-term growth rate of Yorkshire to at least the long-term growth rate of the whole of the UK in accordance with the Long-Term Economic Plan for Yorkshire and Northern Lincolnshire.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","37388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518960","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-27","<p>Pursuant to the answer given on 14 April 2016 to PQ UIN 33354, it is the contract parties that are responsible for the initial negotiation or any renegotiations of PFI and PF2 projects.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-05-27T13:04:14.407Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518960/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518960/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518960/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-18","Public Private Partnerships","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Answer of 14 April 2016 to Question 33354, who is responsible for (a) initial negotiation and (b) any renegotiation of centrally-supported PF1 and PF2 projects.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","37462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518961","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-23","<p>The issues raised are a matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) who are operationally independent from Government.</p><p> </p><p>These questions have been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the honourable member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","37276","2016-05-23T13:53:27.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518961/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518961/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518961/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-18","Directors: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many referrals the Financial Conduct Authority has made to (a) the Insolvency Service and (b) Companies House recommending that a person be disqualified from acting as a company director or investigated further with a view to such action being taken in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","37518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518962","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-23","<p>The Government has fundamentally reformed regulation of the consumer credit market, transferring regulatory responsibility from the Office of Fair Trading (OFT) to the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) on 1 April 2014. This more robust regulatory system is helping to deliver the Government’s vision for a well-functioning and sustainable consumer credit market which is able to meet consumers’ needs.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA has introduced detailed rules regarding firms’ promotions and advertisements. It has consulted on possible new rules, including forbidding financial promotions appearing in or among the rankings of price comparison websites comparing high-cost short-term credit.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-05-23T13:57:22.03Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518962/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518962/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518962/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-05-18","Credit: Interest Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to prevent payday loan companies from advertising financial services from third party companies to customers during the loan application process.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","37469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518963","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-27","This Government supports the system of co-regulation and self-regulation, overseen by the independent Advertising Standards Authority and underpinned by consumer protection legislation. This regulatory system is independent of the Government and is ultimately responsible for setting the standards in advertising, ensuring that all adverts, wherever they appear, are legal, decent, honest and truthful. The Government believes the system has worked well, suitably serving consumers and is sufficiently flexible to deal with both technological advances and new evidence.","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-27T09:21:49.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518963/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518963/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518963/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","Credit: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps the Financial Conduct Authority is taking to enforce rules which prevent misleading advertisement by credit brokers.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","37470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518964","Cabinet Office","false","2016-05-23","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-05-23T16:19:49.853Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518964/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518964/answer","UKSA response to 37539.pdf","UKSA response to 37539.pdf","Referral Letter","Referral Letter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518964/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-05-18","Job Creation: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will estimate how many jobs have been created in Yorkshire since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","37539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518965","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-31","<p>The Department is not reducing delivery of any existing programmes. We are confident that we will be able to meet this new pressure through careful management and review of existing capital budgets. This may include use of receipts from other programmes and re-profiling underspends on capital grant programmes. The reprioritisation of the money means that the Department’s homelessness budget now has an additional £100 million to spend on programmes to help those vulnerable and at risk of homelessness.</p><p /> <p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-05-31T14:49:04.557Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518965/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518965/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518965/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-18","Temporary Accommodation: Sleeping Rough","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the Answer of 18 April 2016 to Question 33117, which programmes the reprioritisation of £100 million in capital funding to deliver low-cost second stage accommodation for rough sleepers will affect.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","37517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518966","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-24","<p>The Government has taken action to help high streets thrive through a range of targeted tax breaks, sensible planning changes and measures to ensure fairer parking for motorists. At Budget, we announced the biggest ever cut in business rates in England – worth £6.7 billion over the next five years, cutting business rates for all ratepayers, and meaning 600,000 of the smallest businesses won’t have to pay business rates again</p><p>We have also given over £18 million to fund successful initiatives such as “Love Your Local Market” and the “Great British High Street Competition”, and have recently announced a digital pilot programme in Gloucestershire, to support town centres and SMEs to compete in the digital era.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-05-24T13:39:44.077Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518966/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518966/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518966/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-18","Retail Trade: Urban Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to encourage businesses into high street premises in town and city centres.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","37419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518967","Department of Health","false","2016-05-27","<p>Information on local authorities’ total spending on physical activity services and facilities for children and young people is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The decision on how much is spent on specific local public health services rests with individual authorities who are best placed to assess local population needs and priorities.</p><p> </p><p>Local authorities are required to undertake Joint Strategic Needs Assessments and to develop Joint Health and Wellbeing Strategies which must inform local authority commissioning plans.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","37358","2016-05-27T13:54:34.903Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518967/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518967/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518967/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-18","Youth Services: Exercise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of spending by each local authority was allocated to provision of facilities and services for children's and young people's physical activity in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","37359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518968","Department of Health","false","2016-05-27","<p>Information on local authorities’ total spending on physical activity services and facilities for children and young people is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The decision on how much is spent on specific local public health services rests with individual authorities who are best placed to assess local population needs and priorities.</p><p> </p><p>Local authorities are required to undertake Joint Strategic Needs Assessments and to develop Joint Health and Wellbeing Strategies which must inform local authority commissioning plans.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","37359","2016-05-27T13:54:34.823Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518968/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518968/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518968/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-18","Youth Services: Per Capita Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment the Government has made of the extent of variation between local authorities in their (a) per capita spending on physical activity services and (b) facilities for children and young people.","false","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","37358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518969","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-25","<p>The Local Government Finance Settlement distributes resources fairly by taking into account the main sources of income available to councils, including council tax and business rates. This means that funding is allocated in a way that ensures authorities delivering the same set of services receive broadly the same annual percentage change in these main sources of income.</p><p>Councils facing the highest demand for services generally continue to receive more funding and have higher spending power than less deprived authorities. In 2016-17 the 10% most deprived authorities received 23% more funding than the 10% least deprived.</p><p>We have also announced a Fair Funding Review to consider the funding needs of different types of areas. This will involve a thorough review of what the needs assessment formula should be in a world in which local government spending is funded by local resources, not central grant. The Review will be done in partnership with the Local Government Association and the wider local government sector, so that all councils have the opportunity to contribute their views.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-05-25T16:14:56.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518969/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518969/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518969/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-18","Local Government Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to reduce regional variations in local authority (a) core spending power and (b) core spending power per dwelling in England.","false","Biography information for Michael Dugher","Barnsley East","Michael Dugher","37275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518970","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-24","<p>The voluntary Right to Buy will give 1.3 million housing association tenants the opportunity to purchase a home.</p><p>For every home sold through the voluntary Right to Buy or the sale of higher value vacant housing, at least one additional home will be built and for every higher value property sold in London, two will be built, increasing overall supply.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-05-24T13:55:13.003Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518970/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518970/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518970/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-18","Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate his Department has made of the likely effect of the extension of right-to-buy and the sale of council properties on the total cost of housing benefit in each year to 2020.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","37243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518971","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-24","<p>DCLG does not have a record of advice given to Lancashire County Council on the formulation of its service planning areas, or requests for such advice.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-05-24T13:38:16.67Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518971/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518971/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518971/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-18","Planning: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what guidance his Department provided to Lancashire County Council on the formulation of its service planning areas.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","37266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518972","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-25","<p>Public libraries are funded and run by local authorities and it is a matter for local authorities to determine how best to provide a comprehensive and efficient public library service to their local community, within available resources.</p><p>Lancashire County Council has a Core Spending Power per dwelling of £1321 for 2016-17 rising to £1392 per dwelling by 2019-20.</p><p>The Department for Culture Media and Sport, together with the Local Government Association, has set up a Leadership for Libraries Taskforce to help public libraries in England build on good practice and add value for the communities they serve. The Taskforce is currently consulting on the attached document at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/libraries-deliver-ambition-for-publiclibraries-in-england-2016-2021" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/libraries-deliver-ambition-for-publiclibraries-in-england-2016-2021</a> which sets out the ambition for public libraries in the future. Furthermore, thanks to Government funding, free Wi-Fi is available to 99% of public libraries in England.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-05-25T16:11:27.6Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518972/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518972/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518972/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-18","Public Libraries: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to support Lancashire County Council in (a) keeping library buildings open and (b) sustaining the function of those buildings as libraries.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","37260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518973","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-25","<p>The Lancashire Enterprise Partnership Growth Deal with Government will invest over £250 million across Lancashire.</p><p>Good progress has been made to date, with 15 out of the 39 projects in the programme underway, and a further 13 due to commence shortly.</p><p>Projects under construction will, amongst other outcomes, support the construction of 850 housing units, create over 2,000 jobs and add over £28 million GVA per annum to the local economy.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-05-25T16:17:07.893Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518973/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518973/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518973/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-18","Economic Growth: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of Lancashire Enterprise Partnership in progressing Growth Deal projects.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","37185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518974","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-25","<p>Eric Ollerenshaw's independent report recognises the successful implementation of Local Council Tax Schemes by local government and makes a number of recommendations to improve their efficiency and effectiveness, whilst remaining a local discount. The Department for Communities and Local Government will consider these recommendations carefully.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","37045 ; 37047","2016-05-25T16:16:36.55Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518974/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518974/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518974/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-18","Council Tax Reduction Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the report Three years on: an independent review of Local Council Tax Support Schemes by Eric Ollerenshaw OBE, published in March 2016, whether his Department plans to take steps to better understand the effect of Local Council Tax Support Schemes on individuals and councils.","false","Biography information for Jon Cruddas","Dagenham and Rainham","Jon Cruddas","37046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518975","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-25","<p>Eric Ollerenshaw's independent report recognises the successful implementation of Local Council Tax Schemes by local government and makes a number of recommendations to improve their efficiency and effectiveness, whilst remaining a local discount. The Department for Communities and Local Government will consider these recommendations carefully.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","37045 ; 37046","2016-05-25T16:16:36.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518975/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518975/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518975/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-18","Council Tax Reduction Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the report Three years on: an independent review of Local Council Tax Support Schemes by Eric Ollerenshaw OBE, published in March 2016, if he will commission in-depth academic research on the effect of Local Council Tax Support Schemes within the wider context of other welfare and socio-economic changes.","false","Biography information for Jon Cruddas","Dagenham and Rainham","Jon Cruddas","37047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518976","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-24","<p>The Government considers that, where areas choose to introduce a directly-elected, region-wide Mayor as part of a devolution deal, this will provide a mechanism to strengthen local accountability and strategic leadership and drive local economic growth. No region-wide elected Mayors are yet in place under the provisions of the Cities and Local Government Devolution Act; the first elections for the new Mayors are being planned for May 2017, subject to Parliamentary approval.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-05-24T13:56:25.24Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518976/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518976/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518976/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-18","Mayors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of the effectiveness of metro-mayors since May 2015.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","37080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518977","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-25","<p>Eric Ollerenshaw's independent report recognises the successful implementation of Local Council Tax Schemes by local government and makes a number of recommendations to improve their efficiency and effectiveness, whilst remaining a local discount. The Department for Communities and Local Government will consider these recommendations carefully.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","37046 ; 37047","2016-05-25T16:16:36.613Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518977/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518977/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518977/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-05-18","Council Tax Reduction Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the report Three years on: an independent review of Local Council Tax Support Schemes by Eric Ollerenshaw OBE, published in March 2016, whether he plans to implement the recommendation to identify how much funding for Council Tax Support is provided to local authorities through the Revenue Support Grant.","false","Biography information for Jon Cruddas","Dagenham and Rainham","Jon Cruddas","37045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518978","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-23","<p>Government fully recognises the outstanding military contribution of Sikhs during the First World War.</p><p>It is for local groups and organisations interested in establishing such a memorial to work with the relevant local planning authority and other organisations to identify a suitable site and obtain the necessary planning permissions.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett",,"2016-05-23T13:40:43.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518978/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518978/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518978/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","World War I: Sikhs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if his Department will consider securing a suitable site in central London for a permanent monument to the death of Sikh people in the First World War.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","37074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518979","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Minister for Culture and the Digital Economy has met and written to the Advertising Standards Authority (ASA), encouraging it to strengthen its rules on broadband speed claims in advertising. We consider that the proportion of customers who can receive the headline speed should be higher than their guidelines stipulate (10%) and have asked to ASA to examine this.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-26T11:58:03.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518979/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518979/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518979/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if his Department will make representations to the Advertising Standards Authority to change the guidelines for broadband speed advertisements to increase the proportion of broadband customers who must reach the stated speed on their internet connection.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","37019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518980","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-25","<p>In April 2015 the previous Government introduced regulations which require authorisation of stakes over £50 on Fixed Odds Betting Terminals through a “verified account” or staff interaction. The Government published its evaluation of the £50 regulations on 21 January. The evaluation paper can be found here: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/evaluation-of-gaming-machine-circumstances-of-useamendment-regulations-2015.</p><p> </p><p>We will now consider the findings of the evaluation before deciding if there is a need for further action.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett",,"2016-05-25T16:11:52.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518980/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518980/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518980/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, by when he plans to open the next triennial review of gaming machine stakes and prizes.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","37147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518981","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-24","<p>The vast majority of phone lines across the UK connect to the nearest telephone exchange via a street cabinet, which can be upgraded to deliver fibre broadband. Estimates are not available of the number of premises served by exchange only lines and therefore when they will all have access to fibre broadband. Exchange only lines present a greater engineering challenge to deliver fibre broadband than those connected via street cabinets but technical solutions are available; one solution is to rearrange the existing network, lay new cables to reroute lines to new cabinets - a technique developed as part of the BDUK Superfast Broadband Programme.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-24T09:37:42.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518981/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518981/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518981/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate his Department has made of when all exchange-only lines will have access to fibre broadband.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","37184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518982","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-23","<p>The rate payable by gambling operators will be informed by this independent economic analysis of the funding of horseracing and further discussion with the betting and racing industries. We will be consulting on the findings of the report with both industries within the next few weeks and intend to publish the report in due course.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett","37211","2016-05-23T13:25:21.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518982/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518982/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518982/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","Horse Racing: Betting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to paragraph 3.2 of his Department's document, Implementing the replacement for the Horserace Betting Levy, published in March 2016, what progress has been made on the independent report on the value of the common interest between betting and racing; and when he expects to publish the findings of that report.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","37210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518983","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-23","<p>TV Licensing have confirmed that the number of black and white TV licences in force in Northern Ireland was 2,978 in 2005, and 736 in 2015.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-23T10:29:24.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518983/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518983/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518983/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many households in Northern Ireland held black and white television licences in (a) 2005 and (b) 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","37225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518984","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-23","Our White Paper, 'A BBC for the Future', makes it clear that we want to ensure that the BBC is transparent and efficient in how it spends its funding. As set out in its annual report, the BBC reviewed the use of Personal Service Companies as a means of engaging presenters and contributors​ in 2012​. ​It continue​s to apply an employment test, discussed with HM Revenue &amp; Customs, to all workers to ensure they have the appropriate employment status.","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-23T13:23:44.023Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518984/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518984/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518984/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","BBC: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the proposals in his Department's White Paper, A BBC for the future, published in May 2016, if he will take steps to ensure that employees earning above £450,000 will not be able to be exempted from the requirement to publish their name by using personal service companies or similar structures.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","37228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518985","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-23","<p>The rate payable by gambling operators will be informed by this independent economic analysis of the funding of horseracing and further discussion with the betting and racing industries. We will be consulting on the findings of the report with both industries within the next few weeks and intend to publish the report in due course.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett","37210","2016-05-23T13:25:21.86Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518985/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518985/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518985/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","Horse Racing: Betting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to paragraph 3.2 of his Department's document, Implementing the replacement for the Horserace Betting Levy, published in March 2016, how his Department plans to use the independent report on the value of the common interest between betting and racing to inform the construct of the proposed levy replacement and recover revenues lost from remote offshore betting.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","37211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518986","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-24","<p>BT’s commercial deployment programme is still ongoing. We will not have access to information on the proportion of cabinets that remain to be upgraded in commercial areas until this is completed.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-24T09:38:50.383Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518986/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518986/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518986/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he has made of the proportion of street level cabinets served by a fibre enabled exchange that are not planned to be upgraded for fibre broadband in commercially viable areas.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","37268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518987","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-25","<p>The Responsible Gambling Strategy Board (RGSB), was set up to by the Gambling Commission to advise on priorities for research, education and training (RET) relating to responsible gambling. The Responsible Gambling Trust (RGT) an independent charity, then commissions research into gambling related harm and funds education and treatment programmes, taking into account the priorities set out by the RGSB.</p><p> </p><p>It is a requirement on all gambling licence holders to make an annual financial contribution to one or more organisations that perform research, education or training for gambling-related harm. The vast majority choose to make that contribution to the Responsible Gambling Trust, which has raised £7.5 million in 2016 (unaudited); £6.5 million in 2015; £6.3 million in 2014; £5.7 million in 2013; £5.2 million in 2012; £5 million in 2011 (each year relates to the previous 12 months to 31 March). RGT’s accounts for these years are available on the Charity Commission website and include the breakdown of expenditure between research, treatment and harm prevention.</p><p> </p><p>RGT is committed to working with RGSB to estimate the cost of the education activities identified in the recently published National Responsible Gambling Strategy, 2016-19, that will be expected to raise from businesses who profit from commercial gambling in Britain.</p><p> </p><p>The Responsible Gambling Trust has published a number of research reports into FOBTs since 2010, which are available on the RGT website: http://www.responsiblegamblingtrust.org.uk/research/research-publications/</p><p> </p><p>Further RGT commercial and independent research on Category B Gaming Machines was published on 24 May, and can be found here <a href="http://www.responsiblegamblingtrust.org.uk/research/research-publications/" target="_blank">http://www.responsiblegamblingtrust.org.uk/research/research-publications/</a></p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett","37241 ; 37245","2016-05-25T13:43:17.623Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518987/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518987/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518987/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","Gambling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what financial provision his Department has made for the (a) research, (b) education and (c) treatment of problem gambling in each year to 2020; and if he will estimate the amount of funding provided by the gambling industry for such activities in each such year.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","37244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518988","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-25","<p>The Responsible Gambling Strategy Board (RGSB), was set up to by the Gambling Commission to advise on priorities for research, education and training (RET) relating to responsible gambling. The Responsible Gambling Trust (RGT) an independent charity, then commissions research into gambling related harm and funds education and treatment programmes, taking into account the priorities set out by the RGSB.</p><p> </p><p>It is a requirement on all gambling licence holders to make an annual financial contribution to one or more organisations that perform research, education or training for gambling-related harm. The vast majority choose to make that contribution to the Responsible Gambling Trust, which has raised £7.5 million in 2016 (unaudited); £6.5 million in 2015; £6.3 million in 2014; £5.7 million in 2013; £5.2 million in 2012; £5 million in 2011 (each year relates to the previous 12 months to 31 March). RGT’s accounts for these years are available on the Charity Commission website and include the breakdown of expenditure between research, treatment and harm prevention.</p><p> </p><p>RGT is committed to working with RGSB to estimate the cost of the education activities identified in the recently published National Responsible Gambling Strategy, 2016-19, that will be expected to raise from businesses who profit from commercial gambling in Britain.</p><p> </p><p>The Responsible Gambling Trust has published a number of research reports into FOBTs since 2010, which are available on the RGT website: http://www.responsiblegamblingtrust.org.uk/research/research-publications/</p><p> </p><p>Further RGT commercial and independent research on Category B Gaming Machines was published on 24 May, and can be found here <a href="http://www.responsiblegamblingtrust.org.uk/research/research-publications/" target="_blank">http://www.responsiblegamblingtrust.org.uk/research/research-publications/</a></p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett","37241 ; 37244","2016-05-25T13:43:17.747Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518988/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518988/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518988/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what research on the effect of fixed odds betting terminals his Department has (a) commissioned, (b) carried out and (c) assessed from external sources since 2010; and whether his Department plans to carry out or commission any further such research.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","37245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518989","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-25","<p>The Responsible Gambling Strategy Board (RGSB), was set up to by the Gambling Commission to advise on priorities for research, education and training (RET) relating to responsible gambling. The Responsible Gambling Trust (RGT) an independent charity, then commissions research into gambling related harm and funds education and treatment programmes, taking into account the priorities set out by the RGSB.</p><p> </p><p>It is a requirement on all gambling licence holders to make an annual financial contribution to one or more organisations that perform research, education or training for gambling-related harm. The vast majority choose to make that contribution to the Responsible Gambling Trust, which has raised £7.5 million in 2016 (unaudited); £6.5 million in 2015; £6.3 million in 2014; £5.7 million in 2013; £5.2 million in 2012; £5 million in 2011 (each year relates to the previous 12 months to 31 March). RGT’s accounts for these years are available on the Charity Commission website and include the breakdown of expenditure between research, treatment and harm prevention.</p><p> </p><p>RGT is committed to working with RGSB to estimate the cost of the education activities identified in the recently published National Responsible Gambling Strategy, 2016-19, that will be expected to raise from businesses who profit from commercial gambling in Britain.</p><p> </p><p>The Responsible Gambling Trust has published a number of research reports into FOBTs since 2010, which are available on the RGT website: http://www.responsiblegamblingtrust.org.uk/research/research-publications/</p><p> </p><p>Further RGT commercial and independent research on Category B Gaming Machines was published on 24 May, and can be found here <a href="http://www.responsiblegamblingtrust.org.uk/research/research-publications/" target="_blank">http://www.responsiblegamblingtrust.org.uk/research/research-publications/</a></p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett","37244 ; 37245","2016-05-25T13:43:17.56Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518989/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518989/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518989/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","Gambling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what funding his Department has provided for the (a) research, (b) education and (c) treatment of problem gambling in each year since 2010; and if he will estimate the level of funding provided by the gambling industry for such activities in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","37241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518990","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-25","<p>The requested information is not held centrally. Local authorities are responsible for the issuing of gambling premises licences, in accordance with the Licensing Objectives and their own Statement of Licensing Policy. Local Authority license registers listing the number of licences in each borough are available to access by the public. The Gambling Commission estimates there are around 2,800 licences in operation in the greater London area, based on feedback from Local Authorities. Haringey Borough Council’s licensing register can be found at the following address: http://www.haringey.gov.uk/business/licensing-and-regulations/licensing/licensing-register</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett","37242","2016-05-25T13:40:51.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518990/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518990/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518990/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","Gambling: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many gambling licenses were issued for premises in (a) Tottenham and (b) Greater London in each year between 2010 and 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","37246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518991","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-25","<p>The requested information is not held centrally. Local authorities are responsible for the issuing of gambling premises licences, in accordance with the Licensing Objectives and their own Statement of Licensing Policy. Local Authority license registers listing the number of licences in each borough are available to access by the public. The Gambling Commission estimates there are around 2,800 licences in operation in the greater London area, based on feedback from Local Authorities. Haringey Borough Council’s licensing register can be found at the following address: http://www.haringey.gov.uk/business/licensing-and-regulations/licensing/licensing-register</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett","37246","2016-05-25T13:40:51.933Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518991/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518991/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518991/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","Gambling: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many gambling licenses were in effect in (a) Tottenham and (b) Greater London (i) in 2010 and (ii) on the most recent date for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","37242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518992","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-23","<p>As part of the discussions leading to the publication of the White Paper, A BBC for the future​: a Broadcaster of Distinction, the government discussed accessibility of the BBC's archive with the BBC. As set out in that White Paper, the government encourages the BBC to do more to open up its archive and ensure that it can be used by the public and as wide a range of institutions and organisations as possible​.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-23T09:49:01.393Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518992/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518992/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518992/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","BBC: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether he has had discussions with the BBC on levels of accessibility to online archived BBC content.","false","Biography information for Michael Dugher","Barnsley East","Michael Dugher","37314"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518993","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-24","<p>Ofcom is the independent body that regulates TV, radio and video on demand services. The Broadcasting Code contains rules those TV and radio broadcasters must follow. There are separate rules for video on demand services which include TV catch up, online film services and libraries of archive content. Government considers this regulatory system is working well and has no plans to hold an inquiry.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-24T09:35:54.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518993/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518993/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518993/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","Mass Media: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if the Government will hold an inquiry into regulation of non-print media.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","37368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518994","Department for Education","false","2016-05-27","<p>The Government’s ambition is that at least 90% of pupils in mainstream secondary schools will enter GCSEs in the English Baccalaureate (EBacc) subjects of English, maths, science, history or geography, and a language.</p><p>The EBacc has been designed to be limited in size to provide a rigorous academic core whilst leaving space in the curriculum for other subjects. On average, pupils in state-funded schools enter nine GCSEs and equivalent qualifications, rising to more than ten for more able pupils.[1] For many pupils, taking the EBacc will mean taking seven GCSEs; and for those taking triple science, it will mean taking eight. This means that there will continue to be room to study other subjects, including arts subjects. A good foundation in the EBacc subjects helps to keep options open for work and further study.</p><p>Since the EBacc was first introduced the proportion of pupils in state-funded schools taking at least one GCSE in an arts subject has increased, rising from 46 per cent in 2011 to 50 per cent in 2015.</p><p>On 3 November 2015 the Secretary of State for Education launched a public consultation seeking views on the government’s proposals for the implementation of the English Baccalaureate.[2] The consultation closed on 29 January 2016 and the government’s response will be published in due course.</p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.compare-school-performance.service.gov.uk/schools-by-type?step=phase&amp;geographic=all&amp;region=0&amp;phase=secondary&amp;for=Key%20stage%204%20performance&amp;basedon=Exam%20entries&amp;show=All%20pupils&amp;&amp;schoolTypeFilter=allSchools" target="_blank">https://www.compare-school-performance.service.gov.uk/schools-by-type?step=phase&amp;geographic=all&amp;region=0&amp;phase=secondary&amp;for=Key%20stage%204%20performance&amp;basedon=Exam%20entries&amp;show=All%20pupils&amp;&amp;schoolTypeFilter=allSchools </a></p><p>[2] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/implementing-the-english-baccalaureate" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/implementing-the-english-baccalaureate</a></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-05-27T12:27:34.35Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518994/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518994/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518994/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-18","English Baccalaureate: Arts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what impact assessment was conducted to identify the consequences of not including arts in the English Baccalaureate.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","37357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518995","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Department holds a number of case studies and research papers with examples of the benefits that museums have on well-being, and has noted the importance of these benefits in the Culture White Paper. Examples of best practice in this area include National Museums Liverpool’s “House of Memories” dementia project, and the 'if: Volunteering for wellbeing' programme at IWM North, Manchester Museum and Museum of Science &amp; Industry, with a particular focus on improving health of participants.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-26T11:51:53.83Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518995/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518995/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518995/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","Museums and Galleries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what information his Department holds on the effect of museums on health and well-being.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","37356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518996","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-24","<p>DCMS and DCLG Ministers and officials regularly discuss matters of shared interest including arts, culture and public libraries.The Culture White Paper which was published in March reflects the close working between the two Departments​.​</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-24T10:24:21.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518996/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518996/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518996/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","Arts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government about the effect on arts and culture of changes to local government funding from central government; and what further such discussions are planned on this issue.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","37354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518997","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-23","<p>The requirement to hold a TV licence will be extended to people streaming or downloading television programmes through on-demand services provided by the BBC (notably iPlayer) and will not include those who listen to radio services.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-23T13:28:04.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518997/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518997/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518997/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","BBC: Video on Demand","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether the Government's proposal to ensure that those who watch BBC iPlayer services are subject to the requirement to pay the license fee will include those who use BBC iPlayer radio services.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","37397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518998","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-26","Decisions in relation to the BBC's online content are a matter for the BBC which is editorially independent of the Government.<p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-26T12:36:52.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518998/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518998/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518998/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","BBC: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will seek information from the BBC on the number of unique visitors to the BBC Food website in each month since May 2010; and if he will place that information in the Library.","false","Biography information for Michael Dugher","Barnsley East","Michael Dugher","37313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518999","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-25","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-05-25T15:13:07.49Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518999/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518999/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/518999/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-05-18","Measurement: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many enforcement cases have been taken by which local weights and measures authorities since Chapter 15 of the Consumer Rights Act 2015 came into force.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","37399"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519000","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-24","<p>No decision has been taken regarding commencement of section 40 of the Crime and Courts Act 2013. The matter is still under consideration.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-24T13:36:43.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519000/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519000/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519000/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","Mass Media: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when the Government plans to bring into force section 40 of the Crime and Courts Act 2013.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","37458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519001","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-24","<p>Criminal proceedings connected to the subject matter of the Leveson Inquiry, including the appeals process, have not yet completed. We‎ have always been clear that these cases must conclude before we consider Part 2 of the Inquiry, including any estimate of cost.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-24T13:36:11.843Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519001/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519001/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519001/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","Culture, Practices and Ethics of the Press Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he made of the cost of Part Two of the Leveson Inquiry.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","37523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519002","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-26","Tech City UK (including Tech North) total operations budget was £2,500,000 in 2014-15; £4,223,000 in 2015-16; and £4,100,000 in 2016-17. Tech City UK (including Tech North) communications costs were £173,091 in 2014-15; £279,355 in 2015-16; and £5,000 in 2016-17 (YTD). These costs were all expenditure on third party communications, consultancy and public relations agencies<p /><p /> Tech North's communication costs were nil in 2014-15 and 2016-17 (YTD), and £74,500 in 2015-16. These costs were all expenditure on third party communications, consultancy and public relations agencies. <p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-26T12:39:27.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519002/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519002/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519002/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","Tech City UK","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what Tech City UK's (a) total operations budget, (b) communications budget and (c) expenditure on third party communications consultancy and public relations agencies was for (i) 2014, (ii) 2015 and (iii) 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","37497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519003","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-23","<p>I have had no discussions with the Royal Parks about the estate yard in Hyde Park. Following my decision this year to increase the capital allocation for the parks, my officials have been in discussion with TRP about rebuilding the existing ageing Hyde Park nursery facility. Planning on this is underway and, subject to relevant permissions, when complete will enable the estate to grow 95% of its plants on site in a new more efficient building.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-23T09:52:03.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519003/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519003/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519003/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","Royal Parks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions he has had with the Royal Parks about the Plantation and the Royal Park Estate Yard in Hyde Park.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","37384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519004","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-23","<p>Responses to all questions in the BBC Charter Review public consultation were analysed and the results published in a Summary of Responses document in April. This document set out the strong support for the continued provision of the licence fee from consultation respondents, as well as significant support for reform or modernisation. On the basis of this, and wider consultation with stakeholders, the government has committed to modernise the licence fee to include BBC on-demand programmes.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-23T09:43:29.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519004/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519004/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519004/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","BBC: Video on Demand","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what account his Department is taking of the substance of responses to Question 11 in the Government's consultation on the future of the BBC published in July 2015, which are set out in Annex 7 of its White Paper, A BBC for the future: a broadcaster of distinction, published in May 2016, in formulating its policy on paying for access to BBC iPlayer services.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","37491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519005","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Department does not hold data on a) and b).</p><p>Between 2012 and 2016, the Department for Education has provided £4.8 million for the “Museums and Schools” programme to support regional museums working with schools, in partnership with National Museums. The programme has exceeded its targets with over 68,000 pupils benefitting, and according to Arts Council England (ACE) data, the number of children attending events at ACE-sponsored museums continues to increase.</p><p> </p><p>c) In the last 12 months, three former local authority-funded museums in England have closed: Snibston Discovery Museum, Orpington Museum and Durham Light Infantry Museum.</p><p> </p><p>Orpington Museum has been replaced with two permanent displays in Bromley Central Library. A section of Durham Light Infantry Museum is now on display at the Palace Green Library, as part of the Somme 1916 exhibition.</p><p> </p><p>Snibston Discovery Museum's collection has been dispersed locally - 61 objects that were on loan from Leicester City Museum Service have been returned along with 40 objects connected to the city's industrial heritage.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-26T13:01:12.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519005/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519005/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519005/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-18","Museums and Galleries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, which museums partly or wholly reliant on public funding, have (a) closed part of their service, (b) reduced educational programmes and (c) closed completely in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","37452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519006","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-26","<p>No chapels owned or administered by the Ministry of Defence (MOD) are part of the pilot project exploring the registration of civil marriages and partnerships or same-sex unions.</p><p> </p><p>The MOD supports same-sex marriage and is committed to ensuring that couples are not disadvantaged by their service. We have concluded a study of serving LGBT personnel to obtain their view on this matter.</p><p> </p><p>Should a same-sex military couple wish to have a civil marriage ceremony on the Defence Estate, it is a requirement that the same access must be granted to all members of the public. The project is attempting to indentify suitable sites for this purpose.</p><p> </p><p>Should a same-sex couple from the Armed Forces wish to get married in a military Chapel they must follow the rules surrounding the marriage of same sex couples (Military or Civilian) in Military chapels, which are laid out in 'The Marriage of Same Sex Couples (Use of Armed Forces' Chapels) Regulations 2014'. At present none of the Churches that send Chaplains to the Armed Forces have opted into the provision of marriage for same-sex couples. Some may seek to change their policy in the future.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-05-26T16:18:21.013Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519006/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519006/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519006/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-18","Military Bases: Religious Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Answer of 9 May 2016 to Question 35843, whether chapels owned and administered by the Ministry of Defence are part of the pilot project exploring the registration of civil marriages and partnerships, including same-sex unions.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","37516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519007","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-24","<p>38 M3 Amphibious Rigs have been in service with the British Army in each of the last six years. No additional rigs have been loaned from the German Army during that time. The planned out of service date for the M3 amphibious rig is 2027; early work is under way to provide a wide wet gap crossing capability in future. No decisions have yet been made about future basing sites for the M3 Amphibious Rig.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The following table shows the number of recorded equipment failure reports (EFR) in each of the last six years.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Calendar Year in which EFR recorded</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>No of EFRs recorded in calendar year</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","37336 ; 37341 ; 37342 ; 37412","2016-05-24T15:07:02.943Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519007/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519007/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519007/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-18","Amphibious Vehicles: Germany","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans the Government has to maintain its fleet of M3 Amphibious Rig bridging vehicles after the withdrawal of UK troops from Germany.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","37413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519008","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Astute class submarines are the largest, most advanced and most powerful attack submarines ever operated by the Royal Navy, combining world-leading sensors, design and weaponry in a versatile vessel. The Royal Navy maintains world-wide deployability with its submarines, this includes under-ice capability.</p><p> </p><p>We do not discuss the detail of such submarine operations, as this would, or would be likely to, prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","37338 ; 37339","2016-05-26T15:24:25.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519008/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519008/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519008/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-18","Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the capacity of the Royal Navy's Astute-class submarines for under-ice operations.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","37448"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519009","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-25","<p>As Minister with responsibility for Cadets, I am aware of the good work Cadet forces do in Northern Ireland and welcome invitations to visit its Cadet establishments. There are no immediate plans to visit Cadet detachments in Northern Ireland but I would be very happy to consider such visits in the near future.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2016-05-25T16:07:17.747Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519009/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519009/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519009/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-18","Armed Forces: Cadets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will visit Army and Sea Cadet detachments in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","37401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519010","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-23","<p>The Ministry of Defence undertakes a wide range of training activity, from phase 1 and phase 2 training for new recruits to complex joint exercises with other nations and specialist training for specific trades and skills, such as nuclear engineering. The costs for these activities encompass nearly all of the Defence Lines of Development and cannot be broken out without incurring disproportionate cost.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-05-23T15:32:21.98Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519010/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519010/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519010/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-18","Armed Forces: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the total size was of the core defence capability training budget in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","37389"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519011","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-24","<p>38 M3 Amphibious Rigs have been in service with the British Army in each of the last six years. No additional rigs have been loaned from the German Army during that time. The planned out of service date for the M3 amphibious rig is 2027; early work is under way to provide a wide wet gap crossing capability in future. No decisions have yet been made about future basing sites for the M3 Amphibious Rig.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The following table shows the number of recorded equipment failure reports (EFR) in each of the last six years.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Calendar Year in which EFR recorded</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>No of EFRs recorded in calendar year</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","37336 ; 37341 ; 37342 ; 37413","2016-05-24T15:07:03.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519011/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519011/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519011/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-18","Amphibious Vehicles: Germany","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many of the German Bundeswehr's M3 Amphibious Rig bridging vehicles were loaned to UK armed forces in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","37412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519012","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-26","<p>The UK has one officer in each of the six NATO Force Integration Units.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-05-26T15:27:05.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519012/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519012/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519012/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-18","Armed Forces: Eastern Europe","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many UK military personnel are currently deployed to NATO force integration units in (a) Bulgaria, (b) Estonia, (c) Latvia, (d) Lithuania, (e) Poland and (f) Romania.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","37344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519013","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-24","<p>38 M3 Amphibious Rigs have been in service with the British Army in each of the last six years. No additional rigs have been loaned from the German Army during that time. The planned out of service date for the M3 amphibious rig is 2027; early work is under way to provide a wide wet gap crossing capability in future. No decisions have yet been made about future basing sites for the M3 Amphibious Rig.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The following table shows the number of recorded equipment failure reports (EFR) in each of the last six years.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Calendar Year in which EFR recorded</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>No of EFRs recorded in calendar year</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","37336 ; 37341 ; 37412 ; 37413","2016-05-24T15:07:03.143Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519013/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519013/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519013/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-18","Amphibious Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many equipment failure reports were recorded in relation to M3 Amphibious Rig Bridging Vehicles in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","37342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519014","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-24","<p>The following table shows the number of personnel from 75 Engineer Regiment who have deployed to train in Germany in each of the last six years.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of personnel </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>115</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>136</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>132</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>These figures do not include personnel from the Regiment who are permanently based in Germany.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-05-24T15:08:33.037Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519014/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519014/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519014/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-18","Armed Forces: Germany","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many personnel from 75 Engineer Regiment were deployed to Germany on training operations in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","37343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519015","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-23","<p>The United Kingdom makes significant contributions to NATO training exercises through the provision of individual staff officers and formed units from all three Services. The information requested will take time to collate and I will write to the hon. Member shortly.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2016-05-23T16:59:21.27Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519015/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519015/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519015/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-18","NATO: Military Exercises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many UK military personnel were deployed on NATO training exercises in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","37390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519016","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Astute class submarines are the largest, most advanced and most powerful attack submarines ever operated by the Royal Navy, combining world-leading sensors, design and weaponry in a versatile vessel. The Royal Navy maintains world-wide deployability with its submarines, this includes under-ice capability.</p><p> </p><p>We do not discuss the detail of such submarine operations, as this would, or would be likely to, prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","37339 ; 37448","2016-05-26T15:24:25.833Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519016/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519016/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519016/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-18","Submarines: Arctic","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, on how many occasions a Royal Navy submarine was deployed to the Arctic region in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","37338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519017","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-24","<p>The UK Armed Forces conduct a wide range of training to operate in cold weather environments. Information on the full range of activities is not held centrally in the format requested and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-05-24T15:09:21.22Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519017/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519017/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519017/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-18","Armed Forces: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many personnel from each branch of the armed forces took part in cold weather training in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","37337"
