"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519250","Department of Health","false","2016-05-24","<p>As set out in the independent Mental Health Taskforce report, Health Education England is working with NHS England, Public Health England, the Local Government Association and local authorities, professional bodies, charities, experts-by-experience and others to develop a costed, multi-disciplinary, five-year workforce strategy. This will focus on the future shape and skill mix of the workforce required to deliver both the Taskforce’s recommendations and the workforce recommendations set out in the Future in Mind strategy for improving children and young people’s mental health.</p><p>Health Education England will also consider the future requirements for training new clinical psychologists and psychotherapists as part of its workforce strategy. Health Education England published its commissioning and investment plan for 2016/17 which sets out plans to commission 526 training places for clinical psychologists in 2016/17 and 43 child psychotherapist places.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-05-24T09:45:56.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519250/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519250/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519250/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-18","Clinical Psychologists","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to ensure that the workforce requirements for the delivery of the NHS England transformation plan can be met with qualified clinical psychologists within the five-year timescale of the plan.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","37447"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519251","Department of Health","false","2016-05-23","<p>The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority (HFEA) is the United Kingdom national regulator for the provision of in vitro fertilisation (IVF). Clinics cannot provide IVF or store gametes and embryos unless they have a licence to do so from the HFEA.</p><p> </p><p>The HFEA’s code of practice (a copy is attached) gives guidance to clinics on the sensitive handling of embryonic material following IVF. It advises that this should be done in a manner that takes account of the special status of the human embryo.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-05-23T10:42:36.25Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519251/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519251/answer","PQ37488 attachment for PQ.pdf","PQ37488 attachment for PQ.pdf","HFEA Code of Practice","HFEA Code of Practice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519251/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-18","In Vitro Fertilisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what guidance his Department provides to clinical commissioning groups on the storage and disposal of embryonic waste following IVF treatment.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","37488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519252","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-24","<p>The information provided in response to Question 33135 dated the 18<sup>th</sup> of April is the latest data available.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-24T12:59:34.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519252/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519252/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519252/answer","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519252/answer/previousversion/232","Biography information for Priti Patel","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-05-18","Employment and Support Allowance: Inflammatory Bowel Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the Answer of 18 April 2016 to Question 33135, on employment and support allowance: inflammatory bowel disease, how many new claimants there have been in this Parliament.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","37490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519253","Department of Health","false","2016-05-26","<p>The NHS Shared Planning Guidance asked the National Health Service to develop proposed footprints for Sustainability and Transformation Plans by 29 January 2016, engaging with local authorities and other partners. The footprints were then reviewed by the national arm’s length bodies, including NHS Improvement, with regard to geography (including patient flow), scale, fit with footprints of existing change programmes, financial sustainability, and leadership capacity. There were one or two areas where further clarification was sought and, following further conversations locally, changes were agreed.</p><p> </p><p>The process for Sustainability and Transformation Plans is designed to bring together health and care leaders to support improvements in health and care based on the needs of local populations. It does not alter the existing accountabilities of clinical commissioning groups, local authorities and NHS provider organisations.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-05-26T13:48:28.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519253/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519253/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519253/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-18","NHS: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which NHS bodies will authorise Sustainability and Transformation Plan footprints; what role NHS Improvement will play; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","37450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519254","Department of Health","false","2016-05-23","<p>The information requested is not currently available centrally. It could only be obtained from NHS Improvement at a disproportionate cost.</p><p>In November 2015, the Government introduced a series of tough financial controls to help the National Health Service tackle overspending on agency staff, including an hourly price cap.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-05-23T13:55:59.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519254/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519254/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519254/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-18","Nurses: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of agency costs as a proportion of the total nursing costs in each NHS (a) trust and (b) foundation trust in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","37434"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519255","Department of Health","false","2016-05-25","<p>The National Stroke Strategy remains valid and implementation of it continues. There are, therefore, no current plans to renew the strategy. Action continues to be taken to ensure the progress made on stroke continues. This includes:</p><p> </p><p>- ongoing work across the country to organise acute stroke care to ensure that all stroke patients, regardless of where they live or what time of the day or week they have their stroke, have access to high quality specialist care;</p><p> </p><p>- publication of the Cardiovascular Disease (CVD) Outcomes Strategy in 2013, which includes many stroke specific strategic ambitions;</p><p> </p><p>- a CVD expert forum, hosted by NHS England, to coordinate delivery of the work which was initiated in the CVD Outcomes Strategy; and</p><p> </p><p>- NHS England’s National Clinical Director for Stroke working with the Strategic Clinical Networks, clinical commissioning groups, voluntary agencies and individual providers to support better commissioning and provision of stroke care.</p><p> </p><p>More generally, the NHS Five Year Forward View recognises that quality of care, including stroke care, can be variable and that patients’ needs are changing and new treatment options are emerging. The Five Year Forward View sets out high level objectives to address these issues.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-05-25T12:52:17.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519255/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519255/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519255/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-18","Strokes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has for a National Stroke Strategy after the end of the ten year strategy plan in 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","37404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519256","Department of Health","false","2016-05-25","<p>The Department’s legal costs are met from individual teams’ existing legal budgets and cannot be broken down further. NHS England also advises that it is not able to provide this information as these are live issues incurring ongoing legal costs.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-05-25T14:07:11.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519256/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519256/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519256/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-05-18","Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what legal costs (a) his Department and (b) NHS England have incurred to date in relation to decisions on access to (i) narcolepsy drugs, (ii) hepatitis C drugs and (iii) pre-exposure prophylaxis for HIV.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","37421"
