"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519338","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-27","<p>Highways England does not hold information on how many motorists were fined as a result of motorway average speed cameras, nor how much were collected in fines, as they are not an enforcement agency. Enforcement is undertaken by the respective police forces.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-05-27T08:55:36.927Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519338/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519338/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519338/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-18","Motorways: Speed Limits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many motorists were fined as a result of motorway average speed cameras in each year since 1985 for which figures are available; and how much was collected in fines in each such year.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","37410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519339","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-23","<p>Since the start of the new Northern and TPE franchises on 1st April 2016, the Rail North Partnership Director (who is responsible for the management of those franchises on behalf of Rail North and the Department) has had one meeting with the Board of Rail North Ltd at which he presented his monthly report.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-05-23T16:57:04.407Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519339/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519339/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519339/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-18","Rail North","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions (a) he and (b) officials in his Department have had with the Rail North Board.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","37428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519340","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-23","<p>The Rail North Partnership Strategic Board currently meets on a monthly basis to oversee the work of the Partnership Management Team.</p><p> </p><p>The Department’s representatives on this Board are the Markets Director, Passenger Services; the Deputy Director Midlands, North &amp; Wales, Passenger Services; and the Programme Director, Network Services.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-05-23T14:31:25.94Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519340/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519340/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519340/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-18","Rail North","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how frequent the partnership meetings between his Department and Rail North are; and who represents his Department at those meetings.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","37429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519341","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-23","<p>The funding arrangements for the Rail North Partnership are a combination of direct funding from DfT to cover the staffing cost that would have been incurred in the management of the two franchises at DfT as well as Rail North Limited membership fees and an allocation of Rail Administration Grant from Combined Authorities. This funding is fixed and indexed. This funding covers all activities undertaken by the Rail North Partnership, including the DfT/Rail North Strategic Board meetings.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-05-23T14:36:58.77Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519341/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519341/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519341/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-18","Rail North","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, who funds arrangements for the DFT Rail North Board meetings.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","37430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519342","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-23","<p>The Rail North Partnership brings together activities that were previously undertaken by DfT and Local Transport Authorities in the North. Accordingly the Government has agreed that £500,000 p.a. of existing annual grant funding provided by the Department to the North of England Passenger Transport Executives (PTEs) and Combined Authorities can be used to fund Rail North. In addition, the Department funds staffing costs that it would have otherwise incurred itself.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-05-23T14:40:15.477Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519342/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519342/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519342/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-18","Rail North: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what funding the Government provides to Rail North.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","37431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519343","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-26","<p>Following the receipt of a formal proposal from Agility Trains West Ltd, My Rt Hon Friend, the Secretary of State for Transport has now approved the conversion of the 21 Class 801 Intercity Express Programme units scheduled for deployment on the Great Western to bi-mode operation. This will enable passengers in the South West and Wales to benefit as soon as possible from brand new trains which will deliver more capacity and more comfort. The first 36 trains will be bi-mode as planned.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-05-26T11:02:12.24Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519343/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519343/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519343/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-18","Rolling Stock: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department has made a decision on the proposed conversion of Class 801 Intercity Express Programme units to bi-mode diesel operation.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","37456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519344","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-27","<p>Ministers have a statutory role in the planning process with regard to transport related planning applications raised on appeal. It would therefore be seen as prejudicial, to comment on or discuss, matters relating to London City airport that are subject to a planning inquiry.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-27T08:18:47.563Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519344/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519344/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519344/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-18","London City Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what account he plans to take of the construction of C-Series planes by Bombardier in Northern Ireland in any decision on London City Airport accommodating  C-Series or similar planes on its proposed new taxiway.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","37444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519345","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-23","<p>The proposed route of Crossrail 2 connects south-west to north-east London via 23 miles of new tunnels between Wimbledon and Tottenham Hale. There are no plans to bring Crossrail 2 through Harrow and Wealdstone station.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-23T13:59:27.373Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519345/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519345/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519345/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-18","Railways: Harrow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress he has made on bringing Crossrail 2 through Harrow and Wealdstone station; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","37485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519346","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-23","<p>The Partnership reviewed the work undertaken by Directly Operated Railways (DOR) in connection with the Direct Awards programme as part of the initial phase of their contract between November and December 2015. This focused on the work done by DOR on the Cross Country Franchise but also included reviewing historic mobilisation plans prepared by DOR for other franchises.</p><p> </p><p>The partnership are not currently advising on any mobilisation plans other than that for the Cross Country Franchise.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-05-23T14:11:32.003Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519346/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519346/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519346/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-18","Railways: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Answer of 12 May to Question 36842, on railways: franchises, whether the partnership referred to in that Answer has provided his Department with advice on mobilisation plans for franchises other than the Cross Country franchise since 1 November 2015.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","37535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519347","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-23","<p>Improving the UK’s air quality is a priority for this Government; we want the UK to have the best natural environment, and clean air is an essential part of this ambition.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s National Air Quality Plan, published on 17 December 2015, sets out a comprehensive approach to improving UK air quality. A key measure of this is the introduction of new Clean Air Zones in five UK cities (Birmingham, Leeds, Southampton, Nottingham and Derby), along with the Ultra Low Emission Zone in London. The Plan will tackle the most polluting vehicles in air pollution hotspots, and will enable us to reach compliance with legal limit values as quickly as possible.</p><p> </p><p>A national scrappage scheme for diesel cars was considered, which included a high-level cost estimate looking at offering grants for scrappage of the dirtiest vehicles.</p><p> </p><p>It was found that even if only offering the scheme to pre-Euro 4 diesel cars only, the costs ran into the billions and impact on emissions was marginal.</p><p> </p><p>This would have minimal impact on compliance with legal limit values for air quality in 2020. It is estimated that 400,000 pre euro 4 diesel cars will remain in the national fleet by this time.</p><p> </p><p>As the costs of a scrappage were considered prohibitively expensive this option was judged an ineffective use of resource, and further analysis was not carried out.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-05-23T14:21:25.067Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519347/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519347/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519347/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-18","Diesel Vehicles: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Answer of 9 May 2016 to Question 36052, on diesel vehicles: exhaust emissions, what estimate his Department has made of the cost of a pre-Euro 4 diesel scrappage scheme; how many vehicles in the UK were estimated to have been potentially eligible for a claim under such a scheme; and whether a benefit-cost ratio was calculated for that proposal.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","37537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519348","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-23","<p>The Franchise Agreement sets out the circumstances which entitle a revision to the Govia Thameslink Railway Schedule 7.1 benchmarks. A predefined contractual change has occurred which has required changes to the Cancellation and TOC Minute Delay benchmarks.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-05-23T14:16:48.12Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519348/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519348/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519348/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-18","Govia Thameslink Railway: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what changes his Department has made to Govia Thameslink Railway Ltd's performance benchmarks under Schedule 7.1 of the Thameslink Southern and Great Northern franchise agreement since that agreement was signed.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","37536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519349","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-27","<p>The Govia Thameslink Railway franchise was let on the basis that farebox revenue belongs to the Department, therefore any risk and opportunity in relation to passenger revenue resides with the Department, including in the event of strike action.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-05-27T08:47:53.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519349/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519349/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519349/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-05-18","Thameslink, Southern and Great Northern Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether revenue risk on the Thameslink, Southern and Great Northern franchise will be borne by the franchisee or the public purse in the event of industrial action.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","37520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/519350","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-23","<p>In response to part a) of your question, spend on cycling in 2015-16 was:</p><ul><li>Bikeability: £11.7m</li><li>Cycle Rail: £14.0m (plus matched funding of £2.10m)</li><li>Cycle Ambition Cities: £15.0m (plus matched funding of £5.10m)</li><li>Highways England: £16.7m</li><li>LSTF: £64.50m</li><li>Local Growth Fund: £60.80m</li><li>Integrated Transport Block: £28.40m</li><li>Transport for London: £145m</li></ul><p><strong>TOTAL: £363.3m, or £7 per head in 2015/16.</strong></p><p> </p><p>Of these programmes, we can provide regional breakdown per head for the Local Sustainable Transport Fund, Cycle Rail, Transport for London and Cycle Ambition Cities, totalling £238.5m.</p><p> </p><p><strong>a) </strong><strong>15/16 regional spend per head (£) for selected programmes</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td rowspan="2"><p><strong>Region</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Regional spend per head (£) for selected programmes</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>East Midlands</p></td><td><p>DfT spend</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total spend</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>East of England</p></td><td><p>DfT spend</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total spend</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>North East</p></td><td><p>DfT spend</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total spend</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>North West</p></td><td><p>DfT spend</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total spend</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>South East</p></td><td><p>DfT spend</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total spend</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>South West</p></td><td><p>DfT spend</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total spend</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2